            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Amaymiya (l-Aʕmāymīya), a small village belonging to the municipality of Sidi Aich (Sīdi ʕĒš), is located in the north of the Gafsa Governorate and therefore close to the governorates of Kasserine and Sidi Bouzid. The municipality’s centre is the town of (Ksar) Sidi Aich, which counts 2,445 inhabitants and is close to the sanctuary of the saint Sidi Aich (Sīdi ʕĒš). The municipality altogether has 8,297 inhabitants and consists of six villages or towns – the central town Ksar Sidi Aich (Gṣaṛ Sīdi ʕĒš) itself, Sidi Aich Chargiya (Sīdi ʕĒš iš-Šargīya), Amaymiya (l-Aʕmāymīya), Menzel Gammoudi (Manzil il-Gammūdi), es-Souinia (is-Swīnīya), Qarya (Garya). Sidi Aich is birthplace to the athlete and first Tunisian Olympic champion Mohammed Gammoudi. Close to the town, but in Kasserine Governorate, there is a water reservoir called Barrage Sidi Aich. To the north east in Sidi Bouzid governorate, there is the Djebel Sidi Aich (Žbal Sīdi ʕĒš) with an altitude of about 839 m. The Oued Sidi Aich is a wadi passing close to the town of Sidi Aich. </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">According to locals, though the soil of the region is fertile, water used to be scarce, making agriculture difficult. However, with the sinking of wells, farmers are able to cultivate more crops. In the region of Sidi Aich olives, pistachios and almonds are grown.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve">To the best of our knowledge hitherto no research has been done on the dialect of Amaymiya, however this dialect is linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project.</p>
            </div>
